The start symbol S can only expand using the rule  
S → NT99 NT89.  
Since the grammar has no ε-productions (no rule of the form X → ε) and no unit productions (rules X → Y with a single non-terminal on the right), each of NT99 and NT89 must ultimately yield at least one terminal symbol. Therefore any string derived from S must have length ≥ 2.

The target string t101 has length 1. Consequently it cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  
S → NT99 NT89  

NT99 has only one production: NT99 → NT6 NT103  
NT6 ⇒ 't108' and NT103 ⇒ 't101', so NT99 can generate exactly the two-token sequence  
t108 t101 – which matches the first two tokens of the string.

The remaining 27 tokens must therefore be generated by NT89.

NT89 has exactly three alternatives:  
1. NT89 → NT61 NT76  
2. NT89 → NT44 NT1  
3. NT89 ⇒ 't60' (a single terminal)

Alternative 3 cannot yield 27 tokens.  

Alternative 2 produces at most 6 tokens:  
• NT1 → NT107 NT17 → two terminals  
• NT44 → NT24 NT88  
  NT24 ⇒ 't123'  or  NT24 → NT54 NT65 (3 terminals)  
  NT88 ⇒ 't141' or 't69' (1 terminal)  
Thus NT44 generates either 2 or 4 terminals, so NT44 NT1 produces 4 or 6 tokens – far fewer than 27.

Alternative 1 requires NT76 to supply one terminal (its only possibilities are 't178', 't45', or 't121'). None of these terminals appears anywhere in the remaining 27-token suffix of the string, so this split is impossible.

Since none of the productions for NT89 can account for the 27-token remainder, NT89 cannot derive the suffix, and therefore S cannot derive the entire string.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
